      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Project Overview</h2>
        <p>Garbage Gary is a touch-screen game developed for the Oyfo technology museum in Enschede, created as part of an assignment at Saxion University of Applied Sciences. The game was designed for children visiting the museum and built to run on a large interactive touch-screen table. The central theme was the effects of littering in nature. Players follow Gary — a little reptile who lives in the forest — who one day discovers a group of people littering at a picnic table and sets out to confront them. Gameplay takes place in a maze where Gary must collect glowing fireflies to light up lamps, while dodging garbage falling from above.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Client &amp; Context</h2>
        <p>The assignment was issued by the Oyfo museum, which wanted a new interactive exhibit aimed at younger visitors. Students were given a choice of educational themes the museum wanted to address, and the team chose littering and its effects on the natural environment. The final product needed to be intuitive enough for children to pick up and play without instructions, and robust enough for repeated use in a public museum setting.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Goals &amp; Challenges</h2>
        <p>The primary challenge was delivering a fully playable, polished game within a six-week window — from concept to a museum-ready build. Coordinating a team of eight people across three disciplines (art, design, and programming) within that timeline required clear task delegation and constant communication to make sure everyone's work could be integrated smoothly. The scope had to be managed carefully to ensure nothing was left unfinished at handover.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Technical Details</h2>
        <p>The game was built in Unity 3D, adapted for touch-screen input on the museum's large display. The role of technical artist covered the full integration pipeline: receiving assets from artists and designers, setting them up correctly in Unity, and bridging the gap between the art and programming teams to make sure everything worked together. One of the more involved technical tasks was setting up the scene lighting to convincingly simulate the dappled, green-filtered light of a forest canopy — creating atmosphere without adding render overhead.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="project-section">
        <h2>Reflection</h2>
        <p>Garbage Gary was a rewarding project precisely because of the team dynamic. Being at the centre of a group of people each bringing their own specialism — and supporting them so they could each do their best work — turned out to be one of the most enjoyable aspects of the whole assignment. Fitting everything together into a coherent product from a range of different inputs is a role that comes naturally, and this project confirmed that leading a cross-disciplinary team is something worth actively pursuing. The tight deadline was stressful, but it also sharpened the ability to make quick decisions and keep things moving.</p>
      </section>

